   841	
   842	    /// When we discover new variables after a runtime check we don't immediately
   843	    /// generate assignments for each of them, because that could lead to wasted
   844	    /// work. Let's consider the following check:
   845	    ///
   846	    /// ```txt
   847	    /// a is Wibble(3, c, 1) -> c
   848	    /// a is _ -> 1
   849	    /// ```
   850	    ///
   851	    /// If we generated variables for it as soon as we enter its corresponding
   852	    /// branch we would find ourselves with this piece of code:
   853	    ///
   854	    /// ```js
   855	    /// if (a instanceof Wibble) {
   856	    ///   let a$0 = wibble.0;
   857	    ///   let a$1 = wibble.1;
   858	    ///   let a$2 = wibble.2;
   859	    ///
   860	    ///   // and now we go on checking these new variables
   861	    /// }
   862	    /// ```
   863	    ///
   864	    /// However, by extracting all the fields immediately we might end up doing
